{
  "Question": "<p>So, I was trying to prove that <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_691\"><math alttext=\"n^{\\frac{1}{n}}\\rightarrow 1\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>n</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>n</mi></mfrac></msup><mo>\u2192</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span> where <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_692\"><math alttext=\"n\\in\\mathbb{N}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>\u2208</mo><mi>\u2115</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span>.</p> <p>Here's what I did:</p> <p>Since <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_693\"><math alttext=\"n^{1/n}&gt;1\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>n</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mi>n</mi></mrow></msup><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span>, let us suppose <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_694\"><math alttext=\"n=(1+k)^{n}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>k</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><mi>n</mi></msup></mrow></semantics></math></span> for <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_695\"><math alttext=\"n&gt;1\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span> and some <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_696\"><math alttext=\"k&gt;0\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span>.</p> <p>Now, I used the binomial expansion and wrote: <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_697\"><math alttext=\"\\begin{aligned} \\displaystyle n&amp;\\displaystyle=1+nk+\\frac{n(n-1)}{2}k^{2}+....+% k^{n}\\geq 1+\\frac{n(n-1)}{2}k\\\\ &amp;\\displaystyle\\Rightarrow n-1\\geq\\frac{n(n-1)}{2}k^{2}\\\\ &amp;\\displaystyle\\Rightarrow k^{2}\\leq\\frac{2}{n}\\end{aligned}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mtable columnspacing=\"0pt\" rowspacing=\"0pt\"><mtr><mtd columnalign=\"right\"><mi>n</mi></mtd><mtd columnalign=\"left\"><mrow><mrow><mi></mi><mo>=</mo><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mi>k</mi></mrow><mo>+</mo><mrow><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mo>\u2062</mo><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u2026</mi></mrow></mrow><mo>.</mo><mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>k</mi><mi>n</mi></msup></mrow><mo>\u2265</mo><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mrow><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mo>\u2062</mo><mi>k</mi></mrow></mrow></mrow></mrow></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd columnalign=\"left\"><mrow><mi></mi><mo>\u21d2</mo><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mo>\u2265</mo><mrow><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mo>\u2062</mo><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mrow></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd columnalign=\"left\"><mrow><mi></mi><mo>\u21d2</mo><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>\u2264</mo><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi></mfrac></mstyle></mrow></mtd></mtr></mtable></semantics></math></span></p> <p>So now, we can always find an <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_698\"><math alttext=\"n&gt;0\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span> such that <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_699\"><math alttext=\"\\frac{2}{\\epsilon^{2}}&lt;n\\Rightarrow\\frac{2}{n}&lt;\\epsilon^{2}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mfrac><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>\u03f5</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>\u21d2</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi></mfrac><mo>&lt;</mo><msup><mi>\u03f5</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></semantics></math></span>.</p> <p>Now, as <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_700\"><math alttext=\"|n^{\\frac{1}{n}}-1|\\geq 0\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">|</mo><mrow><msup><mi>n</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>n</mi></mfrac></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">|</mo></mrow><mo>\u2265</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span>, we have,</p> <p><span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_701\"><math alttext=\"n^{\\frac{1}{n}}-1=k\\leq(\\frac{2}{n})^{\\frac{1}{2}}&lt;\\epsilon\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><msup><mi>n</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>n</mi></mfrac></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>\u2264</mo><msup><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi></mfrac><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></msup><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>\u03f5</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></p> <p>And in this way, I proved that <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_702\"><math alttext=\"n^{\\frac{1}{n}}\\rightarrow 1\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>n</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>n</mi></mfrac></msup><mo>\u2192</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span>.</p> <p>I wanted to know how can I prove this without using Binomial expansion. I tried to do this using the Bernoulli's Inequality,  but couldn't get too far.</p> <p>Any help/hint would be highly appreciable.</p>",
  "Title": "Alternate methods to prove that <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_689\"><math alttext=\"n^{\\frac{1}{n}}\\rightarrow 1\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>n</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>n</mi></mfrac></msup><mo>\u2192</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span> where <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_690\"><math alttext=\"n\\in\\mathbb{N}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>\u2208</mo><mi>\u2115</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span>",
  "Tags": "real-analysis,sequences-and-series,convergence-divergence"
